Initial Gradle-based Android projectThis will serve as base for an Gradle-based AndroidAnnotations project.nnThis makes use of gradle-android-plugin to be processed properly as annAndroid project.  The current 1.0.0 release does not work with AndroidnSDK R14 and higher, due to changes in it's build system.  We thus usen1.1.0-SNAPSHOT deployed in a custom Maven repository for it to work.nnThe androidSignAndAlign configuration is commented out, as we do notnprovide a keystore with this commit.nnThe IDEA plugin is also added to this project, which will be enhanced innthe future to automatically configure AndroidAnnotations in IDEA.  We alsonconfigure the IDEA plugin to download source and JavaDocs automatically,nas well as set the language level to 1.6.nnThis project isn't really limited to just Gradle+IDEA, but more on that Inhaven't used this with Eclipse yet.  Will add it together with configurationnto make it work with AndroidAnnotations.nnSigned-off-by: Ealden Esto E. Escanan <ealden@gmail.com>n

Included AndroidAnnotations 2.2-RC2 as dependencyWe define the API AndroidAnnotations library as a compile-timendependency in Gradle, as we include this in the APK that wengenerate.  The annotation processor JAR is added manually asnwe will simply reference this in both our IDEA and compilenconfigurations to perform annotation processing.nnIdeally AndroidAnnotations is defined in Gradle only, and willndownload both the API and the annotation processor JARs.  Thenlatter would be set to provided as we do not want to include thatnin the APK, and our IDEA and compile configuration would insteadnrefer to the annotation processor in the classpath.  I haven'tnexactly made this work yet :(.nnSigned-off-by: Ealden Esto E. Escanan <ealden@gmail.com>n

Configure AndroidAnnotations for use in IDEAWe modify the actual IPR XML to insert the nodes that are added/modifiednwhen we configure AndroidAnnotations in IDEA manually.nnNote that in the processModule node, the name should match the modulenname of the project you want to provide annotation processing to.nnSigned-off-by: Ealden Esto E. Escanan <ealden@gmail.com>n
Convert HelloAndroidActivity to AndroidAnnotationsSigned-off-by: Ealden Esto E. Escanan <ealden@gmail.com>n

Configuration to process annotations on `gradle assemble`We override compileJava's doFirst method in order to add AndroidAnnotationsnto the compile process.  This allows Gradle to generate the annotations beforencompiling the rest of the code.nnUnfortunately, the generated code is outputted to build/gen instead of simplynthe gen folder.  This means that while the annotated classes are processedncorrectly during a `gradle assemble`, they do not show up inside IDEA and mustnbe rebuilt manually to generate.  It should be possible to point the outputnfolders of both Gradle and IDEA to the same location, but I haven't reallynlooked into that yet.nnSigned-off-by: Ealden Esto E. Escanan <ealden@gmail.com>n

Immediate and delayed executors unificationA ScheduledExecutorService *is* an Executor, so we can use the same tonavoids to create too many threads.nnThe execute(runnable) method becomes a particular case ofnexecute(runnable, delay), with delay=0.nnAs the user can change the executor, delayed executions are notnsupported if the given executor does not support scheduling.nnThis unification paves the way for adding serial execution feature.n

Serial execution in background featureAdds an optional serial attribute to @Background:nn@Background(serial=some_id)nnThis idea comes from #309:nhttps://github.com/excilys/androidannotations/issues/309nnThe principle of this implementation is to keep a separate queue forneach serial identifier, and to give each task to the (unique) executornonly after the previous task with the same serial identifier (if any)nhas completed execution.nnIt guarantees that all tasks with the same serial identifier will bencalled in the order, one at a time (but not necessarily on the samenthread).nnIt is still compatible with the delay attribute. For example:nn@Background(serial=some_id, delay=2000)nnexecutes the task in background after at least 2 seconds *and* after thenprevious task requested with serial=some_id (if any) have completednexecution.n
Test for @Background(serial=some_id)Test if actions are sequential as expected.n

Better task manager implementationThe previous implementation used a set for serial running and a map ofnlists of tasks for managing the serial queues.nnIn practice, there will be very few parallel tasks, using maps andncreating/destroying lists is complex and unefficient.nnA better approach is to use only a list of tasks (only the ones we neednto keep, having a non-null serial) and run through it sequentially fornretrieving tasks.nnMoreover, it is more general, and paves the way for adding a taskncancellation feature.n
Factorize surround with try/catch generationExtract the surround-with-try-catch part of the anonymous Runnablengeneration, in order to reuse it for generating other anonymous classes.n
Directly generate Task instantiationInstead of create a new Runnable instance which will be wrapped by anTask instance, directly create a Task (which is a Runnable).n

Cancellable background tasksAdds an optional id attribute to @Background:nn@Background(id=some_id)nnThe user is able to cancel all background tasks having a specified id:nnBackgroundExecutor.cancelAll(some_id);n
Tests for @Background attributesTests the serialization and cancellation of background tasks.n

Do not fail if cancellation is not supportedIf the executor is replaced by another not supporting cancellation (notnextending ExecutorService), it failed the first time a task with annon-null id was requested.nnNow, it just warns during cancellation.n

But if anmethod is only annotated with Otto annotation, so we do not override it,nthe annotation will not be read Otto and the methods will not be called.nTo help that case, we re-add Otto handlers, which override (andnannotate) Otto annotated methods in the generated subclass.n

Do not extract annotations on Android classesCurrently there is a serious bug [1] in the Android Support library,nwhich is causing processing to fail when extracting annotations fromnancestor classes. The library was compiled with bad options, so somenannotations are missing from the jar. This commit is a workaround fornthe problem: we simply skip the extraction when we encounter a classnstarting with the android package name prefix. This workaround can benpermanent, because this will not effect usage, and also adds a littlenoptimizations, as AA annotations will not be found ever on Androidnclasses.nn1: https://code.google.com/p/android/issues/detail?id=175086

Revert fix possible deadlock in serialized background #1689This reverts commit 99a5170ce231a89d85fb99ce5909a00694eda1b5.nnThis commit broke the serial execution of background tasks. See:n<https://github.com/excilys/androidannotations/issues/1775#issuecomment-223114490>nnFixes #1775.n<https://github.com/excilys/androidannotations/issues/1775>n

Support synchronous executorsBackgroundExecutor assumed that its executor was asynchronous, so thatnin execute(Task), a task could not be removed before it has been addednto the TASKS list.nnHowever, this assumption was wrong with a synchronous executor:ndirectExecute(u00e2u0080u00a6) would execute the task synchronously, leading to callnTask#postExecute(), that removes the task from TASKS. Immediately afternthe execution, directExecute(u00e2u0080u00a6) would add the task to TASKS, which letnthe BackgroundExecutor in an incorrect state.nnTherefore, add the task to the TASKS list before the execution, so thatnit will also work with synchronous executors.nnFixes #1689.n<https://github.com/excilys/androidannotations/issues/1689>n
